{"thought": "First, I need to break this down into logical phases that represent a proven migration pattern. A common high-level structure is: Assessment & Planning → Architecture Design → Pilot Migration → Full Migration → Optimization & Handoff. I should think through each phase carefully to identify the technical dependencies and risks.

For Assessment & Planning, the key will be understanding the current state - this includes database size, schema complexity, data types, dependencies, SLAs, security requirements. This is foundational knowledge needed before any technical work.

Architecture Design phase will depend heavily on the assessment data - choosing between solutions like Snowflake, BigQuery, Redshift, or Synapse based on the assessment findings."}

{"thought": "Now for Pilot Migration - this is critical for risk mitigation. The pilot should be a small but representative subset of data and workload. Dependencies here include having a working cloud environment set up with networking, security controls, and the ability to measure/slice data properly. Key risk is that issues found here could derail confidence in the project.

Full Migration phase will depend on the pilot learnings - specifically the ETL/ELT patterns, data validation processes, and performance benchmarking established during the pilot. This is where parallel runs (old vs new systems) become crucial for risk mitigation.

Optimization phase depends on having monitoring in place from day one of the pilot, so we understand actual usage patterns rather than just theoretical ones."}

